pe\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"30159aa1-626d-4de8-923a-317a4859bbc4\",\"version\":\"2.1.72\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/update-command-mise-detection\",\"slug\":\"snuggly-frolicking-cray\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01BoGUm2Eho5Z88mnjWdHJye\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here's how mise resolves packages:\\n\\n**Mise has a layered resolution system:**\\n\\n1. **Built-in core plugins** — Common tools like `go`, `node`, `python`, `ruby` are handled natively by mise with no external lookup.\\n\\n2. **Mise registry** — A central [registry.toml](https://github.com/jdx/mise/blob/main/registry.toml) that maps short names to backends. When you run `mise install entire`, mise looks up `entire` in this registry to find which **backend** to use and where to get it. The registry entry would point to one of:\\n   - **`ubi:`** (Universal Binary Installer) — Downloads pre-built binaries from GitHub Releases. This is the most common for CLI tools. An entry like `entire = \\\"ubi:entireio/cli\\\"` would tell mise to grab binaries from your GitHub releases.\\n   - **`go:`** — Installs via `go install`.\\n   - **`cargo:`**, **`npm:`**, **`pipx:`** — Language-specific package managers.\\n   - **`asdf:`** — Delegates to an asdf plugin.\\n   - **`aqua:`** — Uses the aqua registry.\\n\\n3. **asdf plugin ecosystem** — If not in the mise registry, mise falls back to searching the [asdf plugin index](https://github.com/asdf-vm/asdf-plugins), which are shell scripts that define how to download/install a tool.\\n\\n**So for `entire` specifically**, it would need either:\\n- An entry in mise's `registry.toml` (e.g., pointing to GitHub Releases via `ubi`)\\n- Or a custom asdf plugin\\n\\nYou can check what mise resolves for `entire` with:\\n\\n```bash\\nmise registry entire\\n```\\n\\nIs this what you were looking for, or are you thinking about how to get `entire` reg